<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="507" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d507">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–1049: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to
                            Major General <persName type="to">Patrick J. Hurley</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-18">November 18, 1944</date>.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>Number 123. I wish you would tell the Generalissimo from me in confidence
                        that a working arrangement between the Generalissimo and the North China
                        forces will greatly expedite the objective of throwing the Japanese out of
                        China from my point of view and also that of the Russians. I cannot tell you
                        more at this time but he will have to take my word for it. You can emphasize
                        the word “Russians” to him.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Roosevelt</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>